</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Solving Simultaneous Equations</P></B></FONT>
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>
<P>In many problems we have to solve two linear equations in two unknowns simultaneously.</P> 

<P>Each equation represents a straight line. The <B>point</B> at which the lines <B>intersect</B> provides the solution. This is a <B>graphical</B> method of obtaining the solution.</P>

<P>The <B>Elimination</B> and <B>Substitution</B> methods can also be used to solve equations simultaneously. These are <B>algebraic</B> methods.<P>

<P>Spend time working on the different methods of solving simultaneous equations (sometimes called Systems of Equations) in Lesson 1-26 
<a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 26 a~?">section a</a>, 
<a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 26 b~?">section b</a>, 
<a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 26 c~?">section c</a>, and  
<a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 26 e 0~?">section e</a>. Then try questions
<a href="launch.htm#q0016">q0016</a> and <a href="launch.htm#q0604">q0604</a>.</P>

<P>Finally study the systems of equations solved in your lecture notes on pages 9 -12.</P>

